00:59:11.420 --> 00:59:17.890
above a Peter Pan collar,
a blue jumper, Mary Janes.

00:59:17.890 --> 00:59:21.290
What novelty has
always promised,

00:59:21.290 --> 00:59:29.970
claiming to first coalesce,
make cleave unto is almost

00:59:29.970 --> 00:59:34.100
as last scattering surface,

00:59:34.100 --> 00:59:38.130
variation in air
pressure, angel voices."

00:59:38.130 --> 00:59:44.310
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That is a poem
that begins with the Big Bang.

00:59:44.310 --> 00:59:45.610
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: Yeah.

00:59:45.610 --> 00:59:46.910
It does.

00:59:46.910 --> 00:59:48.210
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And,
immediately moves to a bus stop

00:59:48.210 --> 00:59:50.060
which is a big, big jump.

00:59:50.060 --> 00:59:51.960
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: Well, the
way the ancient explosion has

00:59:51.960 --> 00:59:53.510
arranged itself.

00:59:53.510 --> 00:59:54.810
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: We are that.

00:59:54.810 --> 00:59:56.110
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: We're that.

00:59:56.110 --> 00:59:57.410
And so, what are we?

00:59:57.410 --> 00:59:59.390
So, with anything you're seeing
is the way the ancient explosion

00:59:59.390 --> 01:00:00.690
has arranged itself.

01:00:00.690 --> 01:00:03.510
It's this room right
here, or at the time

01:00:03.510 --> 01:00:06.230
that I was writing this, that's
what I looked out and saw.

01:00:06.230 --> 01:00:10.200
I guess I was probably in a
car when I had that impression

01:00:10.200 --> 01:00:13.740
of seeing a woman at a bus stop.

01:00:13.740 --> 01:00:15.060
And, thinking, "Hmm."

01:00:15.060 --> 01:00:19.010
Well, there's something touching
about her, something poignant

01:00:19.010 --> 01:00:20.310
that made me remember her.

01:00:20.310 --> 01:00:23.630
And, I just thought, "Well,
that's, that's one thing

01:00:23.630 --> 01:00:27.430
that the Big Bang has arranged
is this moment with her in it.

01:00:27.430 --> 01:00:30.900
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yeah,
it, it's very,

01:00:30.900 --> 01:00:36.110
it's a very theological moment
to be reminded that everything,

01:00:36.110 --> 01:00:40.320
even the most pedestrian
moments are arrangements

01:00:40.320 --> 01:00:44.800
of that ancient,
incomprehensible explosion.

01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:46.640
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: It's
theological if you think

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:51.150
that God ordered up the Big
Bang, but we don't know that.

01:00:51.150 --> 01:00:52.450
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: So,
it's cosmological.

01:00:52.450 --> 01:00:53.750
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout:
Or, I don't know that.

01:00:53.750 --> 01:00:55.050
Maybe you know that.

01:00:55.050 --> 01:00:56.350
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: No,
it's cosmological.

01:00:56.350 --> 01:00:57.650
It's anthological or something.

01:00:57.650 --> 01:00:58.950
Yeah, it makes us, it makes our
ordinary lives seem suddenly

01:00:58.950 --> 01:01:00.320
much vaster.

01:01:00.320 --> 01:01:01.620
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: Yeah.

01:01:01.620 --> 01:01:02.920
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: To
attach it back to that.

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:05.870
I want to end with a poem
that has nothing to do

01:01:05.870 --> 01:01:09.320
with anything we've
talked about.

01:01:09.320 --> 01:01:11.790
Which made me laugh.

01:01:11.790 --> 01:01:13.810
Called "Traveling
Through the Yard".

01:01:13.810 --> 01:01:15.110
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: Okay.

01:01:15.110 --> 01:01:16.500
[ Laughter ]

01:01:16.500 --> 01:01:18.080
Yeah. That's a parody.

01:01:18.080 --> 01:01:23.040
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's
an early book.

01:01:23.040 --> 01:01:24.340
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: Yeah.

01:01:24.340 --> 01:01:30.840
Okay. Well, this does a
version of a famous poem called

01:01:30.840 --> 01:01:32.690
"Traveling Through the Dark".

01:01:32.690 --> 01:01:36.430
That poem, you probably know
it, is by William Stafford.

01:01:36.430 --> 01:01:41.170
So, this is "Traveling Through
the Yard from William Stafford".

01:01:41.170 --> 01:01:46.690
"It was lying near my back porch
in the gaudy light of morning -

01:01:46.690 --> 01:01:52.130
a dove corpse, oddly
featherless, alive with flies.

01:01:52.130 --> 01:01:55.260
I stopped, dustpan in hand,

01:01:55.260 --> 01:01:59.150
and heard them purr
over their feast.

01:01:59.150 --> 01:02:02.910
To leave that there
would make some stink!

01:02:02.910 --> 01:02:06.910
So, thinking hard for all
of us, I scooped it up,

01:02:06.910 --> 01:02:10.040
heaved it across the
marriage counselor's fence."

01:02:10.040 --> 01:02:12.060
[ Laughter ]

01:02:12.060 --> 01:02:13.360
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: All right.

01:02:13.360 --> 01:02:15.110
[ Laughter ]

01:02:15.110 --> 01:02:16.860
It's been such a pleasure
to talk to you tonight.

01:02:16.860 --> 01:02:19.310
Thank you so much.

01:02:19.310 --> 01:02:21.610
[ Applause ]

01:02:21.610 --> 01:02:22.960
&gt;&gt; Rae Armantrout: Thank you.

